@ThinkingandTinkering I've been using them for the last few years. They're great for running DC lights and other low current applications. I have one (a lawn tractor battery) that's hooked to 30 watts of solar panel and it runs a 3 watt light bulb from sunset to sunrise every day. It's been running every day like that for about 4 years now. Great in a power outage.

They actually have a lot of amp hours in them, but a 12 volt conversion of a reasonably good lead acid battery is probably the equivalent of about a 10 volt battery. Fully charged they hold around 11.5 volts. Not too good for use with an inverter, but great for small DC applications. I even have one that is connected to a 9 volt 1 watt hobby solar panel. It runs one of those little (as seen on TV) Mighty Lite's. The early ones that ran on a 9 volt battery. I believe the battery has 2 bad cells, but it still runs that little $10 automatic light (with LDR and motion sensor) faithfully. That one has been running for about 5 years. 

The experiment I want to do is to add an extra cell or two to perhaps a 48 volt battery bank. That should make it hold the proper voltage to be used with an inverter. in my calculations I'm pretty sure 13 cells would be about perfect for a 24 volt alum battery. The problem is you would need 13 equal cells, so in other words they would have to be new cells, and in order to have 13 of them I would either have to design my own battery jug or else use single lead acid cells, which could be very expensive. So far I've only converted old junk batteries.

@ThinkingandTinkering Mate, I just realized, that the UK and AU meanings of the word "Bottler" are the exact opposite... In Antipodes, "bottler" means excellent. as in: "Your blood should be bottled, its so rare."

Not as in "you lost your bottle"

90% of cockney slang translates to OZ just fine, but not in this case.

@offgridwanabe   Make up air is very important.   We have heated with wood stoves for years.   Many had no cold air inlet so they just pulled in cold air to make up for what went up the chimney.   

The amount of heat you can put into a space even with the negative air draw is enormous.   

Outdoor boilers are the bees knees.  That’s what I’ve been using for 4-5 years now.  They eat a ton of wood but the mess and the fire is outside.
